.TH calculate_didt  22.14 "Fri Oct 06 02:12:27 2023" 
.SH Name \fBcalculate_didt\fR \-  Generates the on-die di/dt information from an existing dynamic rail analysis run and saves it in a text file
.SH Syntax  \fBcalculate_didt\fR  [-help]   -net_name <net_name>  -nworst <value>  -state_directory <dir>  [-window_steps <value> | -window_size <value> ] 
.P Generates the on-die di/dt information from an existing dynamic rail analysis run and saves it in a text file. This command allows you to determine the worst N di/dt events for each bump and for the sum of all bumps (vc_sum).
.P 
.SH Parameters    "\fB-help\fR" Prints a brief description that includes the type and default information for each calculate_didt parameter.  For a detailed description of the command and all of its parameters, use the man command:  man calculate_didt  "\fB-net_name <net_name> \fR" Specifies a net for which the di/dt report is to be generated.  "\fB-nworst <value>\fR" Specifies the number of worst windows with the largest di/dt values to be reported per bump.   "\fB-state_directory <dir>\fR" Specifies the name of the state directory where the information on the bump-based di/dt information from the previous run resides.  "\fB-window_steps <value>\fR" Specifies the transient time step size or resolution of the sliding window. The default value is 5.   "\fB-window_size <value>\fR" Specifies the duration of the sliding window in seconds.  Note: The -window_size and -window_steps parameters are mutually exclusive. When both the parameters are specified, the -window_size parameter takes precedence. If you do not specify either of the two parameters, the results will be based on a default of 5 resolution steps. 
.SH Examples
.RS  "*" 2 The following command generates the on-die di/dt information:   calculate_didt -nworst 3 -window_steps 10 -net_name VDD10 -state_directory
./dynamic_rail/core_125C_dynamic_1
.RE 
.SH Related Information
.RS  "*" 2 "Static Power, IRdrop and EM Analysis" in the Voltus User Guide
.RE
.P
